      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "a13b54389f9fccb9",
        "text": "Between the gatherings together, these times of sharing, we are each discovering and learning – new books, new insights. Learning that we can contribute to help accelerate the learning of our other pod members. \n\nWe are becoming a living, learning organism – one that is cultivating ustawi, life overflowing. We sense profound meaning for ourselves and potentially others as we model learning in a new way. \n\nWe wonder, then, if there might be value in reclaiming a tool of learning long known but now largely forgotten, to help us become more empowered learners.\n\nWe speak here of creating a pod experiment of collecting and reflecting using 'commonplace books'. The use of commonplace books can be traced back to Aristotle and other ancients. Seneca, for instance, called them a place to collect ideas and sayings so that one might \"turn them into honey\" with one's own words. \n\nThey were so foundational to the thinkers of the Enlightenment that John Locke wrote a book about them and scholars at Oxford were taught how to use them.  The list of those who used commonplace books to collect and reflect, a practice different from journaling, is extensive, including the likes of Milton, Virginia Wolf, and Newton.\n\nWe live in different times with different tools, a time when the computer can help augment our collective intelligence, our collective wisdom. So it would be with new tools that we might explore unleashing the potential of an ancient practice."
